<br>
The first thing I thought of after reading it was, wow, this is busy with a capital B. There's so much going on that you could be in danger of short changing part of the story. The second thing was, why should I care about this character? <br>
<br>
One of the things that’s so refreshing about manga (and sometimes comic super-hero style) is that the characters are often ordinary individuals placed into extra-ordinary situations OR they are sometimes super powerful beings put into ordinary situations in which they have a difficult time coping.<br>
<br>
Just because she was in the Mars military doesn't tell me enough about why she would become an assassin. That's a pretty huge leap. Maybe the machine did something to her. Maybe it deadened her morality so that she doesn’t know right from wrong and she has to learn that part of being human again. Maybe that was the one thing that Dr. Adachi couldn’t give back to her. He could give her knowledge but he couldn’t re-bond her with humanity. It would make her half way to being a psychopath. This is the fight for her soul and therefore it gives tension to the story. It gives the audience something to hope for her.<br>
<br>
One hole I see in this brief write-up is why Sapphire would be have to try for a regular-person job or even freelance as an assassin. She was a military project. The military tends not to just let that kind of money walk away, but IF before his death her father was able to realize the outcome (a super armed force that could infiltrate society and not feel any remorse over wrong doing) and he and Dr. Adachi came up with a plan to rescue Sapphire from such a fate then it would make more sense. It would also give Dr. Adachi more of a reason to intersect his own daughter’s life with that of Sapphire's, otherwise, as a parent I wouldn’t want her anywhere near my kid.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :o --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/embarassed.gif ALT=":o"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Before dying Dr. Adachi could help her escape the military compound, and then she’s suddenly on her own. The crooked cop could come across her defending herself against multiple attackers and decide to use her. He would give it a good spin – bad guys going free because the cops didn’t have enough evidence to convict, etc., but she really wouldn’t care. Since she hasn’t learned right from wrong she gets sucked into his machinations and some dirty politics before Noa can help her.<br>
<br>
Once they meet up Noa would in effect become Sapphire’s keeper and morality guide on a ordinary daily basis until Sapphire could learn to do that for herself. This could be a mix of heavy lessons and lighthearted humor breaks. A good place for Sapphire to start learning would be on the job…service industry; maybe as a barista at an upscale coffee shop (just because I’m tired of fast food joints<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Both Noa and Sapphire could work together. This would give Noa a much stronger reason to remain Sapphire’s sidekick, and more chance for buddy style interaction, and of course “lessons in humanity” on a daily basis. Noa may or may not believe the cops story and that could play out rather interestingly.<br>
<br>
It also gives you a way for Sapphire and the “hot guy” to meet and get to know one another long before he becomes her target. The contract on him could be the critical mass that makes the click with humanity, starts her thinking on repaired synapses. <br>
<br>
If you don’t go that route, and the Military really did train her as an assassin, then there must be something that makes her predisposed to killing others. Something like bad guys who got away with the murder of her mother - that's pretty cliché too but you get the idea.<br>
<br>
If she’s just going to be bad-ass and kill people for money and not care then the readers won’t care about her either. Even in the movie &quot;Leon, The Professional&quot;, the director/writer has the pro-killer taking in an abused little girl. It’s how we as an audience connect with him, otherwise we wouldn’t care. Sapphire has to have something we care about.<br>
<br>
You’ve obviously given this a lot of thought. Good luck!<br>
